@node "Quick" "Quick start"

  Just start the program up, load an example, and click Go. Listen to the
sound with stereo headphones (this is essential!) while relaxing in a
comfortable chair or lying down, with your eyes closed. The program plays pink
noise (sounds a bit like wind) to mask any noise that might put you off, and a
binaural beat, which sounds like a thrumming tone. To check the stereo channels
aren't being mixed, take one earphone out. If you still hear thrumming,
something is mixing your stereo channels together. Check your amp and your
headphones, and your cables.

@endnode

@node "Binbeainfo" "Binaural beat information"

  The binaural beat is formed in your brain from the two tones played into each
ear. The effect is a tone that varies in volume with a frequency that is the
difference between the frequencies played into each ear. Your brainwaves follow
that frequency and this alters your state.

  Band  | Brainwave frequency | State
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
        |                     |
  Beta  | 12Hz+               | Ready to take in information and respond
  Alpha | 8-12Hz              | Relaxed, task doesn't require much concentration
  Theta | 4-8Hz               | Very relaxed, task requires no concentration
  Delta | 1-4Hz               | Usually asleep

@endnode

@node "Use" "Use"

  To view this manual from the help button in the program, copy a utility that
can display an amigaguide to the program directory, and rename it "ag" (without
the speechmarks :)

  Start the program and dismiss the about requester, and the main window should
appear. The base frequency is the frequency the sine wave is played into one
ear. The frequency into the other ear is the base minus the binaural beat
frequency, which you can change in the next field down. Some values you could
use for the base frequency are:

   Note    |    Frequency (mHz)
   ----------------------------
   C       |    130810
   D       |    146830
   E       |    164810
   F       |    174610
   G       |    196000
   A       |    220000

  The base frequency field is limited to 222000 mHz, because of limitations of
the program and the paula (if you're generating binaural beats another way, it
isn't a good idea for the tone played into either ear to be above 1000Hz because
the sound would be conducted through the skull and would end up in both ears).

  The Frequency field is limited to half the value of the base frequency. Have a
look at the presets for ideas about what frequencies to use.

  Right of those is the pink noise switch. This might help if you live in a
noisy house or something, and it can also help the waves to combine in your
brain, by providing a neutral backdrop. This is the same principle as sensory
deprivation tanks, it makes the brain more susceptible to suggestion.

  It is usually a good idea to sweep to the frequency you want. This reduces the
size of the difference between the binaural beat and the frequency of your
brainwaves. To sweep, tick the box and put the length of the sweep into the
gadget to the right. Put your @{"current frequency" link binbeainfo} into the next gadget down.
A good time to sweep for is about 10 minutes to begin with, and maybe 5 minutes
when you're used to binaural beats.

  If you want a fadeout at the end of the sequence, tick the box and put the
times in. The 'after' time is used whether or not there is a fade out to stop
the sequence and play the wake up noise, if that's activated.

  The total time of the sequence is the fade in (about a second) plus the 'fade
out after' time plus the length of the fade out (if there is one) plus the
length of the wakeup noise (about 100 seconds) if you have that turned on.

  The presets are saved in the program directory, in their own directory. The
samples the program uses are all in the program directory, with sample(1-5).iff
being the pink noise samples. If you want to replace these with your own, they
are played at a period 150. The replacements should all be different, all about
100k long and they should have their periods set to 150. The beep.iff file can
be replaced by any sample that is less than a second long, it is the wakeup
noise. Wave.iff can be replaced by any waveform sample that has a wavelength
of 75 samples (the wave.iff file is a sinewave, which is useful for inducing
low alpha and lower frequencies. The other wave included is trianglewave.iff
which is more useful for high alpha and beta induction. To switch them, just
rename them). All the samples have to be mono. Lastsettings are the settings
that were saved from the gadgets last time the program was quitted. Cinnlogo is
the small logo on the main window. About is the OK button on the about
requester.

  That's that :)
@endnode
